										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p dir="ltr">Whether you‚Äôre in home services, automotive, education, or any vertical in between, managing your business‚Äôs online advertising accounts means keeping track of a bunch of different metrics. You use search impression share to judge how well you‚Äôre performing in the Google Ads auction. You use engagement rate to see whether your messaging is resonating with your Meta audiences. Across <em>both</em> platforms, you turn to click-through rate to determine how compelling your ad copy really is.</p>
<p dir="ltr">But here‚Äôs the thing: If you want to drive substantial returns on your online advertising spend, then achieving <strong>high conversion rates</strong> and <strong>low costs per lead</strong><em>¬†has</em> to stay at the top of your mind.</p>
<p>A key step towards driving high conversion rates and low costs per conversion, of course, is defining what those things look like. What‚Äôs a high Google Ads conversion rate? What‚Äôs a good Meta Ads cost per lead? And how does conversion rate optimization change depending on what industry you‚Äôre in?</p>
<p>These are the questions we‚Äôre here to answer. With this guide, our goal is to provide the essential <strong>conversion rate benchmarks</strong> you need to get your conversion rate optimization (CRO) efforts off to the right start.</p>
<h3>Contents</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#average-google-ads-conversion-rates-by-industry">Average Google Ads conversion rates by industry</a></li>
